node.text: A break from the cold for a winter solstice post (this is a cross post with @ancientartarchive). On the winter solstice sunlight shines through a slit in the rock to illuminate this complex rock art panel in Emery County, Utah (see @jonathanbaileyphoto feed for a picture). This site has engraving that dates from the archaic to modern times. There is also considerable evidence of vandalism as someone tried to take some of the engravings off the rock wall with a chisel. One fof the reasons I started the @ancientartarchive is to digitally preserve and share sites like this.
Reflections on a cold world just in time for the first day of winter. An iceberg, a gentoo penguin and @ianjstrachan all from a trip to Wilhelmina Bay, Antarctica with @lindbladexp and @natgeotravel

More reflections from a cold world. Mt Everest is just impossibly large. I traveled to Gorakshep to make a photo of this huge landscape. @burchamphoto and I spent days hunkered down at the top of Kala Patthar waiting for the right light and weather. Those were a cold few days but so rewarding! #everest

Still thinking about colder times. At 25 degrees below zero (c) this husky ride during a brief arctic day was at once bracing and freezing. Sledge dogs seem happiest traveling at top speed even when that is freezing the passengers! #winter #husky

The looming solstice has me thinking of colder times. Jari Rorn, a Lapland Shaman on a frozen lake near his home in Northern Finland. It was 35 degrees below zero on the lakebed that brief afternoon but Jari still put his bare hands in a hole he had carved in the ice and pulled out fish for lunch.

A big and beautiful Fremont pictograph panel photographer on the San Rafael swell in Emery County, Utah. This image is part of a long term project I am doing with the @ancientartarchive called the Mural of America. The project examines the pre columbian public art tradition that flourished in North America and is still visible on the landscape.

The first time I saw Barrier Canyon Style rock art it sent shivers down my spine. The images painted on rock walls in the American west are haunting. It has always amazed me that artwork 4,000  years old retains its power to communicate emotion. Master platinum-palladium printer Pradip Malde has made a limited edition print to support the @ancientartarchive. We chose one of my photographs of Barrier Canyon artwork for the print (3rd image).
Pradip has produced and edition 12 platinum palladium prints (size 14”x9”) We are asking for a donation to the @ancientartarchive of $1200 or greater. There are only 4 prints left so DM me for details.
The @ancientartarchive is a nonprofit that uses cutting edge digital imaging and VR technology to preserve and share humanity’s oldest stories. #givingtuesday
We got a lot of rain last night.

The Head of Sinbad platinum-palladium print. This spring I photographed an incredible rock art panel called the Head of Sinbad on the San Rafael Swell in central Utah. These figures are Barrier Canyon Style and thought to be 2,000 to 4,000 years old. Master platinum palladium printer @pradipmalde has turned my photograph into an exquisite limited edition print to support the nonprofit @ancientartarchive. We are asking for a $1200 donation to the @ancientartarchive in exchange for a print. Numbers are very limited. DM me for details.

Dog vs Goose swipe left
Coming winter storms reminded me of winters past when my black dog was fascinated by geese on our town's frozen lake. #home #winter

Putnam County, Georgia. Rock Eagle is one of the few Native American effigy mounds in the United States east of the Ohio River. The scale of this artwork is immense. The bird image is made from quartzite rocks, hauled to the site. It is 120 feet wingtip to wingtip—about the size of a 737 jet airliner. Shockingly little is known about the artwork itself. Few cultural remains were found during archaeological digs, but it's estimated that the mound is at least 2,000 years old. This image is part of a project for my nonprofit @ancientartarchive that preserves and shares humanity's oldest stories. #rockeagle #effigymound
Fall comes to Southern Appalachia. An aerial timelapse of a clearing storm in this beautiful part of the world.

An extraordinarily well preserved Fremont rock art panel near Ferron, Utah. It always amazes me that paintings on the landscape survive as long and as well as this one has. Fremont rock art is generally thought to be 2,000-700 years old. Even the youngest dates make this a very old painting. Shot for my nonprofit @ancientartarchive we preserve and share humanity's oldest stories.

My friend @williamalbertallard is having his bi annual print sale. Bill is a legendary @natgeo photographer here is the chance to own one of his prints! Ordering instructions are in his bio @williamalbertallard 
Photo by @williamalbertallard // Buckaroo Ricky Morris Wrangling Horses - Nevada, 1979. Every morning and late afternoon, each buckaroo on the IL cow crew picked one of the five or six horses in their group to ride. Ricky Morris was one of the buckaroos at the IL Ranch, in Nevada. The working cowboy has never made much money but he has had a certain independence. The skills, like wrangling, don’t come with the hat. They have to be acquired and learned. I took this shot in early morning light. The dust acts as kind of a scrim over the picture. But the key to the image is the rope. The line of that rope cutting the diagonal at the back of Ricky’s hand, then the sharp vertical descending to the coil of ropes, which is just off-center of the picture ….that’s the handle for the photograph. Right there.
My obsession with both the night sky and Cedar Mesa continues...

My first trip to Cedar Mesa was over 30 years ago. I drove up one January from Tennessee and spent a frigid week in Grand Gulch marveling at the canyon, the art and archeology. 30 years later this place has still captured my heart. It's a privilege to be working on a @insidenatgeo grant about the artwork in 8 western National Monuments that have been studied for reduction or been reduced by the Department of the Interior. Perhaps the greatest privilege is to be working with representatives of @protectbearsears who's ancestral home I am in. #visitwithrespect

I woke to snow in Santa Fe this morning, but fall was in full effect just a few days ago near Boulder, Utah. This canyon was on fire with color. Sadly this Canyon was also removed from the Grand Staircase Escalante National Monument and is now open for mining and energy exploration.

The night sky twists above the Hoodoos in Grand Staircae Escalante National Monument. This huge expanse of protected land was set aside by Congress in the 1990s. In 2017 the president cut roughly half the land from the Monument leaving it open for mining.

I'm in the American West working on a long term project for the @ancientartarchive called the Mural of America. The project document the vast pre-columbian tradition of public art in North America. This particular morning was devoted to a Fremont petroglyph panel on the San Rafael Swell. #muralofamerica

In 2017 I scaled back my magazine work to start the @ancientartarchive a nonprofit that shares and preserves humanity's oldest stories. In this politically fractured time ancient artwork can remind us of our shared humanity. Follow the link in the @ancientartarchive  profile to join the mailing list and learn more.

After a near sleepless night with wind gusts ripping at my tent I awoke to a beautiful sunrise near the Molen Reef. This part of Utah is beautiful but often harsh. It also conceals some wonderful rock art. I'm here working on my #muralofamerica project for the @ancientartarchive.

I'm hitting the road again for more time in the tent under beautiful Western skies. I'll be working to complete @insidenatgeo grant looking at artwork in Western US National Monuments that have been studied for reduced protected status. It's part of my work with @ancientartarchive to preserve and share humanity's oldest stories.

Fall has finally arrived on my favorite street! This year it has been so hot, so late into the fall. I hesitate to say that individual weather events like the drought and heat we have had this fall are do to the climate crisis but look at the trend. The planet is warming dangerously due to our reliance on fossil fuels. The time to demand action from our governments is now. #climatechangeisreal

My first assignment for @natgeo took me high into the Andes in Peru to cover a team of archaeologists as they excavated human sacrifices on Mt. Ampato. At 19,000 feet a burst blood vessel in my left eye made me go blind in that eye but I stayed on the mountain anyway. The only thing that was important to me was making the pictures. My vision came back and I finished the assignment. 20 plus years and many stories later I look back on that experience as being formative in how I told visual stories. #peru #latergram
